## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Thread.Abort to Cooperative Cancellation

### Pattern Identified: **Timeout Enforcement**

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. Your code uses it to kill a thread that exceeds a time limit. The modern replacement uses `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` with task-based execution.

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block until completion or timeout
            task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Propagate exceptions from the work delegate
        if (task.IsFaulted)
            throw new AggregateException(task.Exception!.InnerExceptions);

        return task.Result;
    }

    // Preferred: async overload
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout,
        CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Explanation |
|---------|-------------|
| **Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive** | If `work` is a tight CPU loop that never checks a token, it will keep running even after timeout. Unlike `Thread.Abort`, nothing forcibly stops it. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Fire-and-forget leaked tasks** | The sync version's `Task.Run` work continues in the background after timeout — it's abandoned, not killed. For true termination of uncooperative code, use a child `Process` + `Process.Kill`. |

---

### If `work` must be cancellable (best practice)

Change the signature to accept a token so work can cooperate:

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return await Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then check the token in loops:
```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in bigList)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

### What Was Removed

| .NET Framework API | Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` / `CancelAfter()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed — not needed with cooperative model |
| Manual `Thread` + `Join` | `Task.Run` + `WaitAsync` |

The fundamental shift: **you no longer kill threads — you ask work to stop, and it must cooperate**.
